    "RoboGeocache": "üî¥ eyJpIjoiNTRXIEhlbnJ5IFN0LiIsIm8iOnsic3RhdHVzIjoiWkVST19SRVNVTFRTIiwiYmxvY2tJbnN0YWxsYXRpb25JZHMiOlsiYmxpTXpHMEhFRjRRU2FMOTAiXSwibG9jYXRpb25GaWVsZElkIjoiZmxkWFVEQ2hpUGdXUEdJRUwifSwiZSI6MTY1MjA1Nzg4NjcxNH0=",
    "Short Description": "Dreamers Coffee House is one of Henry Street‚Äôs newest business residents and at first glance, its polished storefront may look like any other trendy coffee shop. However, once inside the cafe, visitors are greeted by the warm presence of local Chinatown residents and two friendly chatty baristas. For locals Daniel and Sandy, this coffee shop is a passion project to bring together Chinatown residents who are being increasingly displaced by gentrification. Serving up organic brews and other local shop goodies, Dreamers Coffee serves as the neighborhood hangout to swap dreams and community gossip alike.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/dreamers-coffee-house/dreamers-coffee-house-gallery-1.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/dreamers-coffee-house/dreamers-coffee-house-gallery-2.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/dreamers-coffee-house/dreamers-coffee-house-gallery-3.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/dreamers-coffee-house/dreamers-coffee-house-gallery-4.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/dreamers-coffee-house/dreamers-coffee-house-gallery-5.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/dreamers-coffee-house/dreamers-coffee-house-gallery-6.jpg}",
    "Story": "For Daniel, who practically grew up under a Chinese takeout counter, food and beverage come as second nature, and he knew it was only a matter of time before he delved into the industry himself. The idea for Dreamers was first conceived at a senior citizen‚Äôs center. While working as a caretaker, Daniel witnessed the changing landscape of Chinatown over the last seven to eight years. Many of the seniors were being gradually pushed out of their homes by developers who were offering them $150K to move out. These developers had previously gut renovated and replaced many Chinese establishments. Witnessing the slow lights-out of many mom-and-pop shops, Daniel and Sandy built Dreamers Coffee House as a casual spot for locals and newcomers alike to mingle. They find joy in providing a space for the community to come together over coffee.\n\nOpening in January 2020, the shop faced many initial difficulties, especially with early misconceptions about COVID-19 reducing Chinatown‚Äôs foot traffic. Unfortunately, due to its status as a new business, Dreamers Coffee did not qualify for government grants. The shop closed and reopened in June, but traffic has remained slow. Meanwhile, Daniel and Sandy have pitched a number of efforts to connect to the neighborhood and community. They eagerly interact with customers while serving modern drinks like iced London fogs and familiar ones like Cantonese ling mut (honey lemon). In addition, they partner with local businesses and offer them store space to promote their products.\n\nFor the foreseeable future, Dreamers is looking to expand their space and pay off their bank loans. They are looking for ways to keep promoting themselves in order to gain foot traffic and they want to get the word out to the neighborhood that they‚Äôre open for business. Hoping to gain traction, they have been active on Yelp and Instagram. A preemptive closure of Dreamers Coffee would be the loss of another local business and intimate space for Chinatown residents.\n\nDaniel and Sandy have many hopes and aspirations for the shop and need our help to make them a reality. Let‚Äôs pay our way forward and show our support for young Dreamers.",
