    "Short Description": "Go Noodle Nine Moon is a family-owned American Chinese take-out restaurant located in Midtown, Manhattan that started in the 2000s. The restaurant offers over 200 menu items, so customers can order whatever they crave ‚Äî from classics like homemade dumplings and wontons, to Go Noodle‚Äôs signature dishes: Sesame Chicken, Broccoli Chicken, and pan-fried pork dumplings.  Living up to its name as noodle soup experts, Go Noodle also offers more than ten different varieties of the traditional Cantonese noodle soup. Go Noodle takes pride in providing delicious dishes to each and every customer, bringing the warmth and comfort of home with every meal.",
    "Image URLs": "",
    "Story": "Go Noodle is a family-owned restaurant with a story of perseverance and hard work representative of the Chinese immigrant community in New York. Coming from a small village in Fuzhou, the owners immigrated to the U.S. in the late 1990s with just about nothing ‚Äî they had little money, couldn‚Äôt speak English, and knew very few people. Even in Fuzhou, both of them were only formally educated in elementary school. However, despite these early challenges, they never gave up hope and strove to work hard in order to  provide their children with the education that they themselves never had.\n\nUpon arrival, the Yangs were immediately introduced by their relatives to the restaurant business. After working in the industry for more than ten years, they finally decided to take over the restaurant where they had been working, when its previous owners retired.\n\nGo Noodle is one of the few Chinese restaurants in Midtown that offers a menu with both a wide variety of Cantonese noodle soups and classic American Chinese dishes. The Yangs speak fondly of the unforgettable noodle dishes they had at a Cantonese restaurant when they first arrived in NYC‚Äôs Chinatown. These memories inspire their unique menu; their passion inspires their dedication to providing the best American Chinese food to Go Noodle‚Äôs customers.\n\nFor the Yangs, the business is so important to them, that Go Noodle could practically be considered one of their children. Over the past 20 years, the Yangs have invested all of their energy and attention into growing this family restaurant. They never take any breaks except on Thanksgiving, but due to COVID-19, this March was the first time the Yangs had closed  the restaurant in 20 years.\n\nTheir workers are family to them. Despite the economic effects of the pandemic, the Yangs are unwilling to lay off their employees. That loyalty is reciprocated as the employees were eager to continue working even in mid-March. However, since the Yangs were aware of the rapid spread of the virus in China and were concerned for the health of their workers, they made the difficult decision to close the restaurant. After two months of a quarantine that has upended everyone‚Äôs lives, the Yangs have decided to cautiously re-open. Currently, only four of the younger employees are working, while the older employees have been asked to stay home for their well-being until the situation improves.",
