    "Story": "Cutting hair runs in the family for Auntie Ming and her husband. Her father-in-law owned his own barbershop in China, so she decided to follow in his footsteps. When Auntie Ming  moved to the United States, her skills came in handy as cutting hair was one of the only jobs she could do without speaking English. It presented an invaluable opportunity to provide for herself and her loved ones.\n\nOne of Auntie Ming‚Äôs greatest joys from running a hair salon is getting to know and befriending her clients, especially the older customers who visit for the chance to socialize while getting their haircuts. Auntie Ming deeply values the relationships she‚Äôs built with her customers over the years, and Kelly Hair Salon is more than just a place to get haircuts ‚Äî it‚Äôs a place for building community and belonging, especially for those who may find it difficult to do so elsewhere.\n\nHowever, due to COVID, Auntie Ming has been struggling with the rent and bills that keep her business running. The increased costs combined with diminished foot traffic in Chinatown have made it impossible to turn a profit, and Auntie Ming has been putting in her own money to keep the salon afloat.\n\nHelp Auntie Ming maintain not just her livelihood but also  an irreplaceable center of community for the neighborhood.",
