    "Short Description": "Opened on February 15th, 2020, Kuih Cafe specializes in authentic Malaysian cuisine, ranging from desserts such as its namesake, Kuih, to the national dish of Malaysia, Nasi Lemak. Kuih Cafe prides itself in using natural ingredients ‚Äî even down to the food coloring, which is made in-house from plants such as pandan leaf, blue pea flower, ube, red sweet potato, and palm sugar. Kuih Cafe‚Äôs mission is to make traditional Malaysian dishes accessible to the New York community.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-1.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-2.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-4.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-5.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-6.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-7.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-8.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/kuih-cafe/kuih-cafe-gallery-9.jpg}",
    "Story": "Twenty-one years ago, Veronica immigrated to the United States from Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, leaving behind her career as a fashion designer to start a family in New York. Originally a housewife who cared for her husband and daughter, Veronica entered the food industry due to her nostalgia for kuih: bite-sized Southeast Asian pastries composed of glutinous rice and sweet or savory filling.\n\nAuthentic kuih is difficult to find in New York, as this colorful steamed dish is meticulously prepared in a variety of flavors. Veronica took on the challenge of replicating the taste of her hometown, even utilizing the same natural Southeast Asian ingredients. Countless nights of frequenting libraries, consulting family members, and distributing pastries for feedback led to her top recipes: Kuih, Nasi Lemak, and Pineapple Tart Cookies.\n\nPer the advice of her loved ones, Veronica began taking online orders from customers located throughout the city. She found joy in the kindness and support she received, especially on difficult days. To further her expertise, she attended classes at the International Culinary Center and Institute of Culinary Education. \n\nAfter six years of home baking, Veronica was finally able to open a brick-and-mortar location in Chinatown earlier this year. She single-handedly transported equipment and ingredients to the store in a handcart. Every morning, she wakes up at 7 A.M. to prepare for the day. Unfortunately, due to COVID-19, she had to close her doors just a month later. As the only patissi√®re of Kuih Cafe, Veronica is determined to keep her dream alive despite the growing expenses and lack of customers. Help Veronica provide the taste of her hometown to New York  by donating today.",
