    "Short Description": "A cornerstone of Little Fuzhou since 2002, Lanzhou Ramen is a local favorite for its lƒÅ mi√†n. These springy hand-pulled noodles are served in rich, aromatic soup broths with a variety of topping options, including braised beef, tender chicken, and fresh seafood. In addition to their signature noodle soups, Lanzhou Ramen  offers spicy hot pot (m√° l√† t√†ng) and stir-fried noodles.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/lanzhou-ramen/lanzhou-ramen-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/lanzhou-ramen/lanzhou-ramen-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/lanzhou-ramen/lanzhou-ramen-gallery-3.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/lanzhou-ramen/lanzhou-ramen-gallery-4.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/lanzhou-ramen/lanzhou-ramen-gallery-5.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/lanzhou-ramen/lanzhou-ramen-gallery-6.jpg}",
    "Story": "Despite humble origins in a small rural Fujianese village, Owner and Head Chef John has always hungered for more. He started working in restaurants at the age of 15 and has continued doing so ever since. He met his equally ambitious wife when they were both teenagers. Inspired by stories of the American Dream, they moved to the States together in 1998, eventually opening Lanzhou Ramen on East Broadway in 2002. \n\nOperating his own business has been no easy feat for John ‚Äî he speaks little English and struggles to keep up with the rapid change of social media trends. The constant for him has been his dedication to his cooking since life in the restaurant business has been the only life he‚Äôs ever really known. The popularity of his signature dish, the beef hand-pulled noodle soup, is a testament to his hard work and perseverance in mastering the art of noodle-making. \n\nLocated away from the tourist-heavy Canal Street, Lanzhou Ramen relied heavily on local Fujianese customers who would stand in lines in front of the restaurant, waiting for a chance to taste John‚Äôs delectable dishes. But once the coronavirus hit, Lanzhou Ramen, like most other East Broadway businesses, suffered immensely from the loss of foot traffic. Struggling to sustain the restaurant, John has reduced the number of staff members in the last few months. \n\nJohn has been serving delectable noodles out of Lanzhou Ramen for nearly two decades, and some of his staff have been with him for many years. Let‚Äôs help Lanzhou Ramen stay open so that John can continue sharing his delicious food with the community, and enjoy a happy and healthy life with his family.",
