    "Short Description": "For 30 years, New China Beauty Salon on 15 Doyers Street has provided affordable and stylish haircuts to its customers. From fades to buzzcuts, to bobs, layers, and lob cuts, Mr. Dong and his highly adaptable team are willing to cut whatever styles their clients ask for. For New China‚Äôs hairstylists, there‚Äôs nothing more rewarding than seeing a customer light up with renewed confidence and excitement after a terrific haircut.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/new-china-beauty-salon/new-china-beauty-salon-gallery-1.jpg}",
    "Story": "Mr. Dong‚Äôs story starts in 2010, when he immigrated to the United States in pursuit of the classic American Dream. Despite his limited English abilities ‚Äî which restricted his livelihood options to working at construction and renovation sites, restaurants, or hair salons ‚Äî Mr. Dong was determined to find a way to provide for his loved ones by whatever means possible, manual labor included. While his first job was refurbishing printers at a factory, with time, Mr. Dong eventually moved into the hair care services industry as a barber.\n\nIn 2017, the previous owners of New China sold the salon to Mr. Dong, who then took the helm and continued New China‚Äôs tradition of providing trendy and affordable haircuts to the local Chinatown community. Unfortunately, Mr. Dong has fallen onto hard times due to the pandemic, and it has been a struggle to keep up with all the rent, water, and electricity payments, on top of a temporary 3-month closure earlier in 2020.\n\nMr. Dong reflects on how dire the situation has gotten when he explains that he‚Äôs had to raise the cost of a haircut from $8 to $10 ‚Äî something that New China hasn‚Äôt done in over 20 years. Still, the $2 price raise doesn‚Äôt do enough to cover his losses, considering that rent has more than tripled in the last three decades. Mr. Dong notes sadly that keeping the salon open is costing him more money than he can make and just breaking even these days would be considered a relative success.\n\nDespite a significant decrease in business, Mr. Dong doesn‚Äôt want to give up. He has a team of ten hairstylists, who are like family to him, and closing the business would mean putting them out of work. Mr. Dong is determined to see his business through the pandemic ‚Äî let‚Äôs show him that we‚Äôre there beside him as well.",
