    "Short Description": "Rabbit House is truly a one-woman show: Chef Yoshiko Sakuma is the owner, cook, server, and sake sommelier of her solo project on the Lower East Side, serving a signature six-course seasonal omakase with creative wine and sake pairings. Since its opening in 2016, locals have flocked to Rabbit House for Japanese-style small plates and inventive drinks in a cozy and inviting atmosphere. Yoshiko‚Äôs passion for bringing joy to her customers through delicious food and drinks makes each visit to her restaurant a special experience.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/rabbit-house/rabbit-house-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/rabbit-house/rabbit-house-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/rabbit-house/rabbit-house-gallery-3.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/rabbit-house/rabbit-house-gallery-4.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/rabbit-house/rabbit-house-gallery-5.jpg}",
    "Story": "Growing up in Japan as a child of restaurant owners and a grandchild of farmers, Yoshiko has always loved and appreciated fresh food and quality ingredients. She moved to New York in 1996, where she eventually decided to pursue a culinary career, enrolling in a degree in European cooking. After graduation, her passion and talent propelled her through a decade and a half of working in world-renowned restaurants and bakeries across New York, Spain, and Italy.\n\nWhen it was time to finally make her own mark on the culinary world, she returned to the Lower East Side: where her journey began, where her dreams of opening her own restaurant first took root 15 years before. Rabbit House is an expression of Yoshiko‚Äôs lengthy and wide-ranging career as a chef and sommelier, as well as her own heritage. She serves European-influenced, Japanese-style tapas and an omakase prix-fixe meal that changes seasonally, alongside sake and wine pairings, or creative cocktails. Customers mostly come for the omakase, but other favorites include the Addicted Spare Rib, the Trapped Rabbit, and various vegan and gluten-free options.\n\nRabbit House takes its name from its tiny size, like a ‚Äúrabbit hut‚Äù, with only 15 seats in its original location. Yoshiko loves the small size though, explaining that ‚Äúit allows us to be closer to our guests and share good times and memories together.‚Äù The intimacy of the experience is one of the many things that make a meal at Rabbit House special and memorable. The New Yorker described the restaurant as a ‚Äúcozy spot on the Lower East Side, which is so quirky and comfortable that drinking flights of sake at the bar feels like sitting in someone‚Äôs living room.‚Äù\n\nHowever, after COVID-19 hit, Rabbit House saw a 95% drop in business, made worse by the ban on indoor dining. Yoshiko has worked hard to adapt to the challenges of staying open during a pandemic. She started offering delivery and pickup, although some days she would only get a single order. She added ramen offerings for lunchtime and late-night service, available under her Ramen Usagi project, which she runs out of the same space. She even constructed her own tiny outdoor dining structure outside the restaurant! With the return of indoor dining this past February, business has improved, but Rabbit House is not out of the tunnel yet. Let‚Äôs make sure we keep Yoshiko‚Äôs dream alive and simultaneously preserve one of the treasures of the Lower East Side--reserve a table, place an order online, buy gift cards, or donate today!",
