    "RoboGeocache": "üîµ ",
    "Short Description": "In the heart of Manhattan‚Äôs Chinatown, Taiwan Bear House serves up an authentic taste of Taiwan from more than 7,000 miles away with their signature bento boxes, filled to the brim with rice, minced pork gravy, stir-fried cabbage, braised egg, and a wide selection of protein choices. Inspired by the flavors of the night markets of her native Taiwan and longing for comfort food that reminded her of home, Kris Kuo partnered with two friends to open Taiwan Bear House in 2015.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/taiwan-bear/taiwan-bear-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/taiwan-bear/taiwan-bear-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/taiwan-bear/taiwan-bear-gallery-7.jpg}",
    "Story": "When Kris Kuo first moved to the United States to attend graduate school, she felt homesick. She tried to seek out restaurants serving the dishes that would remind her of her hometown of Tainan, Taiwan, but ultimately came up short. Some friends suggested, ‚ÄúWhy don‚Äôt we start our own Taiwanese shop?‚Äù, and the idea of Taiwan Bear House was born.\n\nAt the time that Kris decided to open Taiwan Bear House, she was working as a CPA at an accounting firm. She had no culinary experience, aside from cooking at home for herself or her family. Opening a restaurant was a totally new career path, but she was determined to give it a shot, and to share the Taiwanese classics that weren‚Äôt easily available in Chinatown at the time. Kris decided to focus on bien dang, or Taiwanese bento boxes, a popular comfort food enjoyed by most Taiwanese people, which for her, held specific memories of the night markets of her hometown. To open the restaurant, she enlisted the help of a chef from a famous Taiwan bento box chain store, who briefly came to the United States just to teach her how to source the right ingredients and cook the dishes.\n\nKris and her partners opened Taiwan Bear House in June of 2015, and it has become a destination for not only Taiwanese expats, but also anyone looking for an authentic taste of Taiwan. Popular dishes include the braised pork belly bento and the crispy chicken, which is actually adapted from Kris‚Äôs mom‚Äôs original recipe. A 2016 New York Times review recommended the golden crust pork chop bento, original minced pork bento, night market crispy chicken bento, and fried chicken leg bento. Many customers have personally thanked Kris for helping alleviate their homesickness with her Taiwanese comfort food, and within just a couple years of opening, she had a stable customer base and was even thinking of expanding to more locations.\n\nHowever, the pandemic hit Chinatown businesses hard, and Taiwan Bear House was no exception. Business dropped by at least 40% with the decline in foot traffic and the overnight disappearance of catering events. The streets of Chinatown were dark and deserted, and everyone was worried about their health, so Taiwan Bear House started offering frozen bento box meals that customers could enjoy in the safety of their own homes. Kris had to cut her staff down to just four employees, and she has worked tirelessly during the entire pandemic just to keep her restaurant running. She takes on both front-of-house and back-of-house duties‚Äîshe cooks, works the register, packs orders for takeout, and more. Despite Kris‚Äôs hard work and perseverance, it has been a challenge to pay the rent and the bills. To make matters worse, although Taiwan Bear House is located on Pell St. in the heart of Manhattan‚Äôs Chinatown, it was deemed ineligible for certain NYC small business loan programs because it technically shares a zip code with wealthier neighborhoods such as SoHo and TriBeCa.\n\nAlthough the past year has been a struggle, Kris still finds pride and joy in having her own shop that she started from scratch. To her, Taiwan Bear House‚Äôs story shows that entrepreneurship, and women-owned businesses, can succeed. Let‚Äôs make sure Kris‚Äôs small business can continue to succeed, and keep sharing delicious Taiwanese comfort food with this city.",
