    "Short Description": "Ting‚Äôs Gift Shop is a decades-old family business, now run by Eleanor Ting. Serving as a cultural bridge across generations, the items in this shop can bring people together, as it has existed long enough to have serviced this generation‚Äôs grandparents. Because of Ting‚Äôs dedication to tradition and history, it has for decades been a place where nostalgic adults return to, many for childhood toys that they can‚Äôt find anywhere else. Eleanor also enjoys breaking down the symbolism and significance of traditional cultural goods in a way American-born Chinese will understand.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-3.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-4.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-5.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-6.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-7.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-8.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/tings-gift-shop/tings-gift-shop-gallery-9.jpg}",
    "Story": "Ting‚Äôs Gift Shop opened in 1958, and was one of the first gift shops in Manhattan‚Äôs Chinatown. Eleanor‚Äôs family opened the store shortly after immigrating to New York. They have safeguarded a treasure trove of antiques over the generations; many of the items they sell today were directly imported from Hong Kong and Japan artisans in the 50‚Äôs and 70‚Äôs. Just the other day, a customer bought an incense burner from the 1965 World Fair!\n\nThe gift shop was meant to cater to the Chinese locals, who still make up the majority of customers. Many are loyal for life, patronizing the store during visits back to NYC even after they‚Äôve moved. The Chinese customers often haggle and bargain; consequently, the store has adopted an unofficial price-matching policy.\n\nBest-selling items are representations of the Three Wise Men, Buddhas, and Tie Guan Yin. When younger customers visit, they are often looking for pieces of nostalgia or cultural reckoning. A recent customer in her 20s shopped with the intention of buying everything her grandma had owned in her apartment. Others have looked for toys they played with as kids many years ago.\n\nDue to COVID, Ting‚Äôs Gift Shop was forced to close in March and only reopened in September. Many days, there are no customers, as foot traffic in the area has decreased significantly - Ting‚Äôs first customer since reopening was at the end of October.\n\nEleanor always looks forward to returning clientele like that customer, who‚Äôs made Ting‚Äôs her first stop whenever she gets paid. But the cold weather, dark hours and quiet pedestrian traffic makes staying open a financially difficult decision.\n\nLet‚Äôs support Eleanor in keeping this 62-year-old Chinatown stronghold open for generations to come.",
