    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/toniis-steamed-rice-roll/toniis-steamed-rice-roll-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/toniis-steamed-rice-roll/toniis-steamed-rice-roll-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/toniis-steamed-rice-roll/toniis-steamed-rice-roll-gallery-3.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/toniis-steamed-rice-roll/toniis-steamed-rice-roll-gallery-4.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/toniis-steamed-rice-roll/toniis-steamed-rice-roll-gallery-5.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/toniis-steamed-rice-roll/toniis-steamed-rice-roll-gallery-6.jpg}",
    "Story": "Tonii‚Äôs grand opening in 2019 marked a new era for the Yee family, who have been in the Chinatown restaurant business for nearly 30 years. The Yees started off with Kam Hing Bakery on Baxter Street, and eventually moved it to Bayard Street, where Tonii‚Äôs is currently located. The family also owned a branch of the bakery in Brooklyn, but recently closed it due to the overwhelming effects of the ongoing pandemic; now, all their businesses operate out of Tonii‚Äôs.\n\nThe Yees work hard to keep their small business afloat, and family is the driving force behind this determination in more ways than one. Elizabeth, who manages the restaurant, hopes to give her parents a break, while simultaneously providing for her own children by maintaining the family business. To her, working at Tonii‚Äôs is more than just a job ‚Äî it‚Äôs also about carrying on the family legacy. The famous sponge cake recipe, originating from Elizabeth‚Äôs grandfather, has been passed down through the Yee family, and Elizabeth sees the restaurant as a way for future generations to remember their family heritage and culture.\n\nHowever with recent events, carrying on the family business has grown increasingly difficult. Many of Tonii‚Äôs employees left once the pandemic hit in March, and while the wellbeing of customers and staff is Elizabeth‚Äôs priority, she has encountered some challenges navigating the new safety measures. Given Tonii‚Äôs proximity to a construction zone and location on the bustling Bayard street, it is difficult for Elizabeth to provide outdoor dining.\n\nNevertheless, the Yees hope to persevere and make the most of their situation ‚Äî let‚Äôs do what we can to help them.",
