    "Short Description": "Wing Hing Seafood Restaurant has been serving the Brooklyn community together since 2014, bringing their passion for Cantonese cuisine to locals and visitors. Wing Hing‚Äôs story is intertwined with those of their workers, whose diverse immigrant backgrounds have allowed them to bring different perspectives to Cantonese cuisine.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant-gallery-3.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant/wing-hing-seafood-restaurant-gallery-4.jpg}",
    "Story": "Hing has been working in Cantonese restaurants in Hong Kong since he was a teenager. He has been in and out of kitchens, making a living with the only trade he‚Äôs ever known.\n\nHing‚Äôs culinary journey in the States began when he left his home city in the late 80s. Following his passion for Cantonese cuisine, he immediately started working for a small Chinese restaurant. Little did he know, this would also lead him to his wife, who worked the front-of-house at that very same restaurant. Together, they decided to return to their roots to start a family.\n\nMoving back to Hong Kong gave Hing the opportunity to further perfect his craft, as he worked for various restaurants across the city over the course of six years. However, this sanctuary of complete familiarity was short-lived. The family decided to move to New York City to take care of Hing's mother and provide their daughter Yuki with better opportunities. From his humble beginnings cooking in restaurant kitchens to now managing Wing Hing Seafood Restaurant, Hing has revitalized his American Dream.\n\nHing started out at Wing Hing Seafood Restaurant as a chef. Before he knew it, four years flew by and he was deeply invested, working long hours and devoting the bulk of his energy to the establishment; as he grew closer to fellow staff members, they became his second family.\n\nWhen the opportunity came for Hing to take on the management reins, he took the chance to reshape the restaurant by accentuating the establishment‚Äôs Cantonese roots. Despite New York City‚Äôs merciless restaurant culture, he was willing to take the risk‚Äîhoping that his passion would allow Wing Hing Seafood Restaurant to thrive.\n\nHowever, sacrifice was necessary. Hing had to transition from normal working hours to fifteen-hour workdays. In Chinese restaurants, there is dim sum and lunch service, a break, then dinner service. For Hing, however, there were few breaks; between services, he was always out running errands and making sure everything would be set for evening service. After evening service, he‚Äôd stay to help clean and close up. He was always the last to leave. Despite the long hours, it is Hing‚Äôs dedication that allows him to provide his customers with the freshest ingredients while maintaining affordable prices. Through traditional Cantonese recipes, he/Wing Hing created a safe space for Chinese Americans: families are brought together, helping later generations reconnect with their culture.\n\nInspired by her parents‚Äô perseverance in achieving their own American Dream, Yuki hopes to own her own restaurant one day. Yuki mentions, ‚ÄúI worry for the future of the restaurant‚Äîthere are so many uncertainties with the current COVID-19 situation. Some restaurants will make it out of the crisis, but many will shutter. Still, I want to remain optimistic. After all, all we can do is hope for the best.‚Äù\n\nWing Hing plays an integral role in the lives of Hing, the staff members and their families, as well as the families of the community it serves. ‚ÄúEvery Sunday, my family would go to get dim sum at Wing Hing. It was a family tradition,‚Äù an anonymous community member says‚Äîa sentiment echoed by many.",
