    "Short Description": "Although Chinatown today is typically tourist-filled and family-friendly, gangs ruled its streets in the 1980s, when Winnie‚Äôs Bar first opened. Through all the transformations the neighborhood has undergone over the years, the local dive bar has managed to stay true to its mission and culture. Winnie‚Äôs has always been about comfort, community, and fun enjoyment ‚Äî it‚Äôs a place where customers can get together with their friends, kick it back with Winnie‚Äôs famous Dragon Punch, and karaoke all through the night.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/winnies-bar/winnies-bar-gallery-1.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/winnies-bar/winnies-bar-gallery-2.jpg,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/winnies-bar/winnies-bar-gallery-3.jpg}",
    "Story": "Winnie‚Äôs Bar first opened in 1987, when Owner Winnie took over the previous establishment at 104 Bayard Street at the suggestion of a close bartending friend. Winnie herself knew almost nothing about running a bar at the time, and her first set of regulars were local Chinatown gangsters; this was not, by any means, Winnie‚Äôs intended clientele, but simply reflective of the gang-dominated nature of Chinatown nightlife in the late 80s.\n\nAs Winnie gained experience running her bar, she developed a steady stream of loyal customers who always returned for the vibrant community and the chance to sing their hearts out. (One particular customer loved the bar so much that he even brought in Scarlett Johansson and Christina Richie on two separate occasions.) Journey‚Äôs ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt Stop Believing‚Äù was constantly booming in the background as bar-goers sipped on the specialty red Dragon Punch ‚Äî Winnie‚Äôs boozy take on the classic Hawaiian Punch.\n\nThrough the years, the bar has garnered a number of different reputations (gangster bar, bridge and tunnel bar, hipster bar, NYU bar), but one thing about Winnie‚Äôs has never changed: people return to Winnie‚Äôs time and time again for a laid-back, no-frills experience because they know they‚Äôll all be treated and welcomed the same. Maintaining the friendly culture at Winnie‚Äôs is no coincidence, though. Winnie‚Äôs son, Manager Teddy, explained that they intentionally pick employees who can strike up a conversation with customers even during an intense karaoke session, because their goal is to get customers to be as comfortable and as stress-free as possible when they‚Äôre hanging out at Winnie‚Äôs Bar.\n\nIn 2015, Winnie lost her Bayard Street lease due to the rising rent rates, and that was thought to be the end of a Chinatown legend. To the delighted surprise of many, Winnie‚Äôs Bar made a comeback four years later on 58 East Broadway and business was going strong until the economic effects of COVID-19 hit Chinatown in early 2020, forcing Winnie‚Äôs to temporarily shut down. Winnie and Teddy plan to reopen in the first week of November with social distancing measures and safety precautions carefully put in-place.\n\nWe can keep this Chinatown stronghold from closing down again by donating to them below. In the words of Journey, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt. Stop. Believing!‚Äù",
