    "Short Description": "Since its founding in the 1990s, Wonton Noodle Garden has been serving delicious and affordable wontons to Chinatown tourists and locals alike. The owner, Ben, and his family has managed the restaurant for three generations and is dedicated to preserving traditional dishes for future generations to come.",
    "Image URLs": "{https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wonton-noodle-garden/wonton-noodle-garden-gallery-1.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wonton-noodle-garden/wonton-noodle-garden-gallery-2.PNG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wonton-noodle-garden/wonton-noodle-garden-gallery-3.JPG,https://storage.googleapis.com/sendchinatownlove-assets/public/assets/wonton-noodle-garden/wonton-noodle-garden-gallery-4.PNG}",
    "Story": "For Ben, safeguarding the future of Chinatown restaurants is a life mission. The restaurant has been in the family for more than twenty years after it was passed onto them  from close friends. From grandfather to father to son, their number one priority has never changed ‚Äî make high-quality, delicious food at an affordable price.\n\nBen has been interested in the hospitality industry since childhood ‚Äî not out of desire for money, but out of a desire to build impactful companies. A true entrepreneur, he studied business management in college, which has helped him transition Wonton Noodle Garden into the modern era, while continuously learning about digitization on the fly.\n\nBen still eats wontons almost every day. What‚Äôs special about these wontons is that they‚Äôre made differently than the traditional Cantonese style wonton. This results in wontons with an aromatic, succulent mixture of pork and shrimp, setting them apart from other restaurants‚Äô in flavor and texture. \n\nDuring difficult times like the present, customers are what motivate the family to continue operating the business. Ben‚Äôs greatest joy is in keeping up with regulars while expanding the customer base to younger generations. With no business from tourists these days, Ben is relying on returning local customers to keep the restaurant running. Even so, he‚Äôs having a hard time maintaining staff numbers and wages (he‚Äôs had to let go 6 out of 12 employees due to COVID). \n\nLet‚Äôs help Ben support his employees and further his mission to save traditional Chinatown restaurants, so that future generations can enjoy Wonton Noodle Garden‚Äôs delicious offerings!",
